### 3. UGCGallery — Instagram Social Wall (client component)

**Reference:** Posh Brows ends the homepage with "SHOW OFF YOUR BROW SKILLS — TAG US using your favorite POSH BROWS products for a chance to be featured on our Instagram!" followed by a grid of real client/creator videos. This is the highest-converting social proof section on beauty brand sites.

**This is the most complex of the three priority components.**

**Architecture:**

The Instagram Basic Display API provides a long-lived token for your own account. The Express backend polls this API every 6 hours and caches results in PostgreSQL. The Next.js frontend fetches from your own `/api/instagram/feed` — not directly from Instagram. This means:
- No CORS issues
- No rate limit exposure on the client
- Content survives Instagram API outages
- You control which posts display (approved status in DB)

```ts
// api/src/services/instagram.service.ts
// Responsibilities:
// - Exchange short-lived token → long-lived token (60 day refresh)
// - Poll GET /me/media?fields=id,media_type,media_url,thumbnail_url,permalink,timestamp
// - Upsert into instagram_posts table
// - Cron: refresh every 6 hours

// Entity fields:
// id, instagram_id, media_type (IMAGE|VIDEO|CAROUSEL_ALBUM),
// media_url, thumbnail_url, permalink, timestamp, approved, featured
```

**Frontend UGC Gallery component requirements:**
- Masonry or uniform grid — 4 columns desktop, 2 columns mobile
- Each cell: square crop, `object-fit: cover`
- VIDEO type posts: render as muted autoplay loop (same pattern as hero)
- IMAGE type posts: render via imgproxy for WebP + resize
- Hover state: gold overlay with Instagram icon and "View Post" link
- Clicking opens the `permalink` in a new tab — never embed Instagram's own iframe
- "Follow us @handle" CTA below the grid — ghost button, gold border
- Section header: "AS SEEN ON OUR CLIENTS" in Cormorant Garamond, tracked wide
- Subhead: "Tag #kassythreads to be featured" in DM Sans muted

```tsx
'use client'

// Fetch at page level (RSC parent) and pass as prop — do not fetch inside the client component
// This keeps the social wall data in the static render, not a client-side waterfall

export function UGCGallery({ posts }: { posts: InstagramPost[] }) {
  return (
    <section className="ugc-gallery">
      <header> {/* section heading */} </header>
      <div className="ugc-grid">
        {posts.map(post => (
          <UGCCell key={post.id} post={post} />
        ))}
      </div>
    </section>
  )
}
```

**Data fetching in RSC parent:**
```tsx
// In (marketing)/page.tsx
const posts = await fetch(`${process.env.API_URL}/api/instagram/feed?approved=true&limit=12`, {
  next: { revalidate: 21600 } // ISR — revalidate every 6 hours, matches cron
}).then(r => r.json())

return (
  <>
    <VideoHero />
    <GifProductSection />
    {/* ... */}
    <UGCGallery posts={posts} />
  </>
)
```

